Up Saga in a Nutshell Saga acts as file centralization system that ties working spaces ​ By tracking how files (knowledge) are sent to other working spaces, Saga can add huge improvements to how we view our work and Saga Workings ​ The Input Output Problem: With most work processes, there are a chaotic delivery of Inputs and outputs between departments and ​ Often these handoffs are done through dumping them in a shared drive and with some email Emails are lost and the shared drive starts behaving like a folder ​ Over time the files and emails are lost resulting in lost knowledge and ​ Solution: ​ Saga allows users to version control their own working space while maintaining direct connection to other user s work ​ Saga provides user the ability to assign input and outputs to individual files and track each version of the file and the corresponding messages between sender, reciever and other ​ "Folder Dump" Problem: Without Proper Version control, working folders often turn into a folder dump that sorely needs context to properly understand the files and ​ Solution: Saga provides version control capabilities to allow to track the different versions of files within a directory and in between ©2021 by Proudly created with   Configuration Management | Saga | Marietta Home Survey How Saga Works Contact Download Saga More Use tab to navigate through the menu Sign In Who should wear a medical ID? Diabetes - Heart problems and implants - (angina pectoris, atrial fibrillation, pacemakers - Anticoagulant treatment) - Drug allergy - Food allergies (eg peanuts) - Insect allergies (eg bee stings) - Alzheimer s disease, memory Hypertension - Institutional risk - Pulmonary disease (asthma, COPD) - Renal failure - Emphysema, breathing disorders - Anemia, blood diseases - Epilepsy, seizure disorders - Hearing, visual or mental disorders - Children with special needs (autism) - Tourette s syndrome - Surgery , transplant and cancer patients - Participation in clinical People Taking Multiple Drugs - Rare Disease Blood Type - Sickle Cell Disease - Caregivers - Gastric Bypass Surgery - Arrhythmias - ADD ADHD - Patients With Bariatric Surgery - Cerebral Palsy - Cystic Fibrosis - Mental Health Patients - Multiple Parkinson s Disease - Patients in Clinical Trials Allergic reactions to drugs, food, or insects can cause serious health The Medical Identifier informs medical personnel about allergies, allowing them to quickly respond to serious allergic Allergens are Here are some common examples: Anticonvulsants: Carbamazepine (Tegretol), lamotrigine (Lamictal) - Analgesics: aspirin ibuprofen (Advil, Motrin) - antibiotics: penicillin, amoxicillin, cephalosporins (cefaclor), mycins (erythromycin) - drugs: codeine, morphine - food: nuts, wheat, dairy products, soy - others: horse serum, insect bites, datex , dye: FAQ Who should wear a medical ID? Since many investment decisions are made on a relative basis, itâs for founders and investors to have access to shared data sets that can help strengthen alignment and improve While the conversation about DTC valuations has benefitted from prominent voices in the community, we saw the need for a more comprehensive, evergreen There are good reasons why this hasnât previously Creating a single set of useful benchmarks is difficult in a space primarily occupied by private Data is scarce, numbers are difficult to trust, and itâs unlikely that any single data set can be applied universally across companies with varying categories, price points, and business But itâs important to start somewhere, and with your support and feedback, we hope this resource can continue to grow in valuable for all those involved in the DTC Leading brands choose Drivepoint Ready to see what you can do with Drivepoint? A SmartPool leverages the strength of Smart Contracts in a blockchain to enable transparent, processing of a miner’s shares and payment is in a long term journey to push the boundaries where Smart Contracts can be used in a traditional Mining Typically, Mining pools maintain statistics and payment data in private repositories, which are then exposed via API to a User Such mechanisms do not provide assurance that miners are rewarded for their actual shares, and leaves obfuscation in the way of A SmartPool achieves transparency by storing payment and shares data directly on the In the case of , we launched our first phase of our ERGO SmartPool by holding payments exclusively in smart contracts, which are validated and accessible via the blockchain Read more in our FAQ on how is leading the smart contract innovation! GETBLOK SMARTPOOL Utility One of the initial goals of is to provide miners a way to create among themselves, thereby allowing miners to choose how they get The SmartPool provides the base framework for to work and will ensure that smart contracts control the payment through every possible GETBLOK SMARTPOOL How does it work? Each payment distribution handled by the Smart Pool is considered an “epoch”. Each epoch represents the state of the SmartPool and the distribution it performed at any given All of the important information used by the smart pool to distribute its payouts are stored This, in combination with the rules laid out by the smart contracts, ensure that changes made to the smart pool are visible by In addition to the transparency it provides, the SmartPool is made to be modular and can change itself to support new payment methods and types of This ensures that new features can be added while still staying transparent about what these features can Join our small communitity! Medical Community Information | Pinnacle Medical Products Home About Product Contact Us Medical Community Information How does the Sequential Automated Turning (S.A.T.) System Address Patient and Nursing Safety Issues? Patients who are immobile are at highest risk of developing hospital acquired pressure injuries (HAPIs). Ensuring regular movement or using repositioning redistributes pressure and helps prevent pressure Keeping patients moving is a key component of pressure injury prevention Repositioning is important for patients who are unable to move around easily Nurses need to be competent in the use of devices that help with repositioning (1) Preventing HAPIs can be nursing intensive, and the challenge is even more difficult when there is nursing staff turnover and Studies suggest that HAPI development can be directly affected by the number of registered nurses and time spent at the bedside (2). Patients with HAPIs had significantly higher mortality rates across stages, as well as higher risk of readmissions at , and post hospitalization, compared with patients without HAPI (3). By preventing HAPIs, hospitals have the potential to reduce unreimbursed treatment expenditures, reduce length of stay, minimize readmissions, prevent associated complications, and improve overall outcomes for their patients (3) The System utilizes automated technology to address patient safety related to HAPI The system is designed to automatically turn and reposition patients frequently in order to reduce the risk By using the SAT system, patients are safer as a result of: Automated turning and repositioning patients moving and frequently repositioned as often as every minutes to every 2 hours Ease of use addresses nursing staff competency with the device and ensures that patients are correctly turned and repositioned The automated technology reduces nursing workload burden by serving as a patient turning and repositioning aid, which is especially important in the current climate of high turnover and national staffing shortages The is designed to prevent HAPI, thereby reducing length of stay, minimizing readmissions, preventing associated complications, and improving overall patient References: Fletcher J (2020) Pressure ulcer education 5: keeping patients Nursing Times [online] : 2, Horn, , Buerhaus, , Bergstrom, , & Smout, (2005). RN staffing time and outcomes of nursing home residents: pressure ulcers and other adverse outcomes are less likely as RNs spend more time on direct patient The American journal of nursing , (11), –71. https: doi.org 10.1097 00000446-200511000-00028 Wassel, , Delhougne, , Gayle, , Dreyfus, , & Larson, (2020). Risk of readmissions, mortality, and conditions across pressure injury (HAPI) stages in a US National Hospital Discharge International wound journal , (6), –1934. https: doi.org 10.1111 iwj.13482 In any healthcare facility, the goal is to take the best possible care of With that said, for immobile or deconditioned patients, it is important for caregivers to frequently turn and reposition Our innovative product makes quick work of turning those patients as One caregiver can do the job with little or no effort at The Sequential Automated Turning system consists of two inflatable wedges that are positioned beneath the An air hose extends from the bottom of each wedge to an air pump that is connected to the foot of the bed or placed on the Once the wedges are in place, all the user has to do is plug the air hoses into the inlets in the air pump and choose whether to sequentially inflate and deflate every minutes, every hour, or every two After that, it works with a simple push It will inflate one side for the predetermined time, then deflate that and inflate the other It continuously, automatically, and sequentially turns the patient left or right at least to degrees, which is the standard range for turning patients to avoid pressure Easily adjusted to accommodate the patient’s needs, it can be used on almost any bed surface and does not require additional equipment or bed modifications to operate (many competitors require modifications to beds or additional equipment installation in order to utilize the product). Frozen Donor Eggs | Fertility Lane About Danielle Lane Vivian DeLima Resources Parents Egg Donors Frozen Donor Eggs Donor Eggs Explained Fees Explained Traditional Donation When Payments Are Due Blog Contact Us More Use tab to navigate through the menu Book Appointment Frozen Donor Eggs Start Here Frozen donor eggs can be Wherever you are in your donor egg journey, we re here to help every step of the Choose which area interests you most to learn Donor Eggs Explained Fees Explained Why Choose Frozen Donor Eggs? There are several advantages to using frozen donor First, these eggs are typically already frozen, or the donor is scheduled to freeze her eggs in the immediate This allows for a quicker cycle for you, the recipient parent(s). In general, the eggs can be shipped to your clinic and used as quickly as the clinic can schedule your There is no waiting for the donor to be available to cycle, no chance that she won’t get any eggs and no risk that she won’t pass This can save you both time and money as the ​ Additionally, some companies will actually reimburse their employees for the expense of frozen donor This is an advantage to using a fresh egg donor whose services are typically difficult to get And in the case of not having reimbursement, the expense of frozen eggs can be more tailored to your specific For example, many egg banks sell eggs in groups of minimum eggs, and most will allow you to purchase additional eggs a la carte as needed to meet your family In this way, you can purchase only what you will likely A typical egg donor will be predicted to produce greater than eggs with some producing up to Very few recipients will use eggs in their family planning needs, but in the case of a fresh egg donor, you will end up paying for all of those eggs in most If you are hoping to have children, that may be appropriate, but if your goals are only children, then you may benefit from fewer eggs and therefore a less expensive In short, costs per treatment cycle are generally lower using frozen eggs because many of the costs are shared among more than one ​ Finally, many clinics still synchronize the cycle between the fresh egg donor and the recipient While this is not necessary given the vast experience with frozen embryo transfers, if your clinic is choosing to do this, it will require a certain level of coordination between you and the fresh egg Alternatively, your embryo can be frozen after it is made using fresh donor eggs and the embryo can be transferred on a schedule convenient for This is almost always done in cases where the embryo is biopsied and tested genetically prior to embryo transfer (pre-implantation genetic testing). Limitations To Frozen Eggs There are some limitations to frozen eggs as For example, frozen donor egg banks are not required by law to report success rate data to the government the same way as fertility And although individual clinics do report their success rates with frozen donor eggs, there is no way for you, as a patient, to discern that a certain frozen egg bank is producing good quality eggs associated with pregnancy ​ An additional issue is that most frozen egg banks will not provide comprehensive historical data on the past cycles of a frozen egg donor or whether prior frozen eggs from a given donor resulted in This makes it challenging for clinics and patients to have the same confidence in frozen donor eggs as they do in fresh egg donors where this information is readily Currently, according to the SART (Society for Assisted Reproductive Technology) website or the CDC website, the national average for live births using frozen eggs is lower than that of fresh In data from SART from , the live birth rate from frozen eggs was percent, while the rate from fresh eggs was However, this varies significantly from clinic to clinic depending on their individual experience and technical In fact, some programs have reported rates with frozen donor eggs that are equivalent to fresh donor Also, it is reassuring that no difference has been demonstrated in malformations between children born after vitrification of oocytes and those born through IVF in ​ Overall, the added convenience and the lower cycle cost of frozen eggs should be balanced against the lower success rate in some programs and the lower number of eggs available in order to determine the best approach for Choosing the right approach to egg donation is critical to your goals and Working with our team and reproductive endocrinologist in concert with any other members of your fertility team will help you build your family with How We Differ From Other Egg Banks Like many things in fertility, not all egg banks are created Unfortunately, it is difficult to compare costs, guarantees, and donor We believe that certain criteria make us Our egg donors are all physician recruited and screened by our own reproductive Each protocol, egg retrieval and freezing (vitrification) process is handled by the same Eighty percent of our e

epidemiologists We are practitioners who have spent decades working in local and district health agencies, fighting outbreaks , and doing the difficult and messy work of building the foundational health and data systems upon which public health insights The pandemic has put an intense spotlight on the discipline of epidemiology, most prominently on health officials and academic But worldwide, most actionable epidemiological insight and impact derives from practitioners working at the local level - data managers, epidemiologists, public health practitioners, and clinicians who collect operational data, analyse trends, and communicate findings to guide strategic response to health needs in their local Applied Epi emerged to support these frontline practitioners, and we started by addressing an unmet need in applied The story of Applied Epi begins with the Epidemiologist R Handbook Applied Epi emerged to address an unmet need in applied In while working the epidemiological frontline of response, Applied Epi Neale Batra and Alex Spina found themselves fielding similar requests from colleagues all over the Over and over, they heard from public health responders who wanted to use R, a free, analytical software, but lacked accessible R training materials relevant to their tasks on the R has been used in other disciplines for years but only recently in public Now, R’s flexibility, capabilities, brilliant visualizations, and sleek automated reports were proving invaluable in the pandemic Unfortunately, R remained inaccessible to many public health responders who needed it Existing R training materials for health audiences were either focused on academic epidemiology, assumed familiarity with computer science, or were Building a grassroots movement In November , Neale and Alex convened an independent group of collaborators who worked in their spare time to create The Epidemiologist R Handbook - a manual specifically addressing the analytical challenges facing frontline Partners like MÃ©decins Sans FrontiÃ¨res and TEPHINET (a global network of field epidemiology training programs) and accelerated production of the Widespread adoption On May , the Epi R Handbook launched and within hours had been viewed by more than ,000 Volunteers offered to translate the handbook into 9 languages, and it was rapidly adopted into training curricula at universities, government agencies, and field epidemiology training Within six months, over ,000 people had used the handbook, including ,000 people in and With the user community rapidly expanding and requests for collaboration arriving from all sides, it was decided to form the organization Applied Epi to sustain and build upon the Epi R From hours to minutes Since launching the Epi R Handbook, we have been inundated with stories of how transitioning to R has had dramatic impacts for epidemiologists working all over the In one story, a Haitian epidemiologist described how he used to struggle for hours each week in Excel with tedious, uninspiring, and After several months of learning R with the Epi R Handbook, those same weekly analyses now take minutes and are agile, robust, and Beyond R: our vision for epidemiology that is more advanced, efficient, standardized, accessible, and equitable For Applied Epi, R is the starting place, but it is a vehicle to reach larger Standardized code leads to standardized methods By implementing a standard analytical language, we open the door to standardisation of epidemiological Applied Epi is convening practitioner and academic stakeholders to consolidate and validate the currently varied approaches to surveys, sampling, outbreak response, reporting, and Smoother emergency response Response entities use a variety of tools to assess situations, analyse data, and produce Adoption of R as the common analytical language will improve collaboration and reduce duplication of More competitive epidemiologists from the global south R is a programming skill that users in settings can use to advance their careers and transform the capabilities of their local health More accessible and practical epidemiology training Currently, aspiring epidemiologists face barriers such as high tuition, visa restrictions, limited seats, and curricula that do not address the challenges of frontline Applied Epi is developing educational pathways that
